This award supported the Front Range Number Theory Day (FRNTD), a new,one-day biannual miniconference whose location alternates between theUniversity of Colorado and Colorado State University.



The Front Range of Colorado is mathematically rich but geographicallyisolated. The goals of FRNTD include:

connecting people interested in number theory who live in the Front Range and creating a platform for collaboration;
learning about new research problems and techniques, especially those complementary to the interests of local researchers;
nurturing a bigger and stronger local number theory community of students, postdocs, and faculty;
generating excitement for number theory not just among local graduate students, postdocs, and faculty, but also among local undergraduates;
providing a welcoming platform for early career researchers, both local and not, to share their work; and
generating interest in and helping disseminate the results and work of local number theorists.




To this end, over the course of ten FRNTD's, we had thirty different speakers. (Each FRNTD had a mix of local speakers and visitors; and one talk was typically explicitly intended to be accessible to undergradutes.) Moreover, each FRNTD has a session for contributed lightning talks from graduate students. A detailed schedule is available at theconference website,
https://sites.google.com/view/frontrangenumbertheoryday/



In surveys after each conference, participants consistently stated that they felt more connected to, and aware of, opportunities and progress in number theory on the Front Range.


